Here's the complete migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-related patterns that don't exist in modern .NET:

| Old Pattern | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Just return the result |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `true` triggers `Thread.Abort` | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown in .NET 8 | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End â€” return a FileResult instead.
        // The framework handles Content-Disposition and ContentType.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult RedirectAfterProcess()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect() returns a RedirectResult â€” no Thread.Abort,
            // no boolean endResponse parameter.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No catch (ThreadAbortException) â€” it is never thrown in .NET 8.
        // Swallowing it was only needed because Response.Redirect(url, true)
        // used Thread.Abort as a control-flow mechanism.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key pitfalls to watch for

**1. Don't write to `Response` manually for file downloads.** In ASP.NET Core, return `File()`, `Content()`, or `Results.*` â€” the framework owns the response lifecycle.

**2. Remove all `catch (ThreadAbortException)` blocks.** `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8, so `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. These catch blocks are dead code. If they contained cleanup logic, move it to `finally`.

**3. `User.Identity` can be `null`.** ASP.NET Core doesn't guarantee a non-null `Identity`, so use null-conditional access (`?.IsAuthenticated`).

**4. Every action must return `IActionResult`.** In Web Forms, `Response.Redirect` + `Response.End` short-circuited execution mid-method. In MVC/Core, you `return Redirect(...)` â€” code after a redirect call **will still execute** unless you return.

**5. No `Response.End()` equivalent exists.** If you have middleware or filters that wrote directly to `Response.Body`, use `HttpContext.RequestAborted` (a `CancellationToken`) for long-running work, and simply `return` to end the response.
